      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1784698556476,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "In this problem we are given an n*n matrix and we need to rotate it 90 degrees. As i saw the problem required you to shift around the elements of the elements of the array in place\nthe key is to do it inplace without  using a considerable extra space. To really know what is rotation i advise to just look at the problem statement again.\n ",
      "fontSize": 124,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "In this problem we are given an n*n matrix and we need to rotate it 90 degrees. As i saw the problem required you to shift around the elements of the elements of the array in place\nthe key is to do it inplace without  using a considerable extra space. To really know what is rotation i advise to just look at the problem statement again.\n ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "a6eI31zTxs-etziPG3TKZ",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 5016.739910798434,
      "y": -5597.91884332806,
      "width": 13379.3544921875,
      "height": 1240,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#f08c00",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "hachure",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 2,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b3I",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 228545979,
      "version": 1779,
      "versionNonce": 416414918,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1784699520841,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "1. To solve this i first noticed a pattern of shifting the outer shell of the matrix around. and i noticed if i did this recursively till i reached the core i would be able to solve it\nThe since this approach felt easier to understand i began working on the boundary conditions and how i would code it. i broke the problem down into functions then coded those functions quite\neasily myself. to rotate any specific shell around i noticed i only ever needed 4 arrays to store the state of the matrix positions that i overwrite. i also noticed that if i used some funcky logic i would be able\nto save some of the space and need only a bunch of variables like just 3 for doing this, but since i was losing momentum thinking too much about the indices and working out the correct boundary and overriting conditions\ni just decided it be better to just store the arrays and then easily rewite them later. then i did this initilization and rewriting step by step each time going inside along the diagonal and tracking all the variables.\nand when i reached the core that would be when there's just a single element in the middle in case of odd n*n or just a 2*2 inner matrix in case of any even n*n.\nand when i reached that i just returned the recursion flow when n got equal to or below 1; and voila solved it eaily at first i though it wouldn't get accepted becuase of large time or space complexity\nbut i worked out my solution works for O(n^2) time and O(n) space as it uses 4 arrays of size n. This is my own divide and conquer i guess.",
      "fontSize": 124,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "1. To solve this i first noticed a pattern of shifting the outer shell of the matrix around. and i noticed if i did this recursively till i reached the core i would be able to solve it\nThe since this approach felt easier to understand i began working on the boundary conditions and how i would code it. i broke the problem down into functions then coded those functions quite\neasily myself. to rotate any specific shell around i noticed i only ever needed 4 arrays to store the state of the matrix positions that i overwrite. i also noticed that if i used some funcky logic i would be able\nto save some of the space and need only a bunch of variables like just 3 for doing this, but since i was losing momentum thinking too much about the indices and working out the correct boundary and overriting conditions\ni just decided it be better to just store the arrays and then easily rewite them later. then i did this initilization and rewriting step by step each time going inside along the diagonal and tracking all the variables.\nand when i reached the core that would be when there's just a single element in the middle in case of odd n*n or just a 2*2 inner matrix in case of any even n*n.\nand when i reached that i just returned the recursion flow when n got equal to or below 1; and voila solved it eaily at first i though it wouldn't get accepted becuase of large time or space complexity\nbut i worked out my solution works for O(n^2) time and O(n) space as it uses 4 arrays of size n. This is my own divide and conquer i guess.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "_GSUBEuybhtTFaYDvuY_y",
