      "seed": 483233542,
      "version": 1479,
      "versionNonce": 823837318,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1784700963617,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "3. Ouh oh! well i did think of those transpose had to mean something here. and offcourse if am i to do anything good here in computer science i must must learn linear algebra pretty good to you know make my easier here when i am actually working with higher level vectors/ 2d matrices etc.\nso it turns out i had made an optimal solution but the space complexity can be reducted to O(1) by doing doing the rotation part a bit better. like rotate the corners by storing one in a temp variable then move inwars and rotate those places as well. for any rotation we just need a single varaible instead of 4 n sized arrays\nwhich is really a massive win. and i noticed that n^2 solutions for an n^2 input size is just linear processing so our algortihm is really linear compared to the input size and that's what matters. Oh yeah the transpose and reversing each row in place will also do the job and is the more industry standard way as it avoids\nany kind of index arithmetic so there is less chance of mistracking and making and error plus adds to the reaadability of code in large systems and that too takes n^2 time and constant space so yeah we won. we just have to optimize our rotate function otherwise my approach of solving it was quite correct.",
      "fontSize": 124,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "3. Ouh oh! well i did think of those transpose had to mean something here. and offcourse if am i to do anything good here in computer science i must must learn linear algebra pretty good to you know make my easier here when i am actually working with higher level vectors/ 2d matrices etc.\nso it turns out i had made an optimal solution but the space complexity can be reducted to O(1) by doing doing the rotation part a bit better. like rotate the corners by storing one in a temp variable then move inwars and rotate those places as well. for any rotation we just need a single varaible instead of 4 n sized arrays\nwhich is really a massive win. and i noticed that n^2 solutions for an n^2 input size is just linear processing so our algortihm is really linear compared to the input size and that's what matters. Oh yeah the transpose and reversing each row in place will also do the job and is the more industry standard way as it avoids\nany kind of index arithmetic so there is less chance of mistracking and making and error plus adds to the reaadability of code in large systems and that too takes n^2 time and constant space so yeah we won. we just have to optimize our rotate function otherwise my approach of solving it was quite correct.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
